issue.title: nghttp2 1.57.0 limits responses to 33 per second
issue.body:
After updating to 1.57.0, I see that performance tests against my server are now limited to 33 queries per second (with the initial pool of 1000) due to the recent https://github.com/nghttp2/nghttp2/pull/1961.
This seems to show up as ```nghttp2_session_want_write()``` and ```nghttp2_session_want_read()``` both returning 0.
By calling ```nghttp2_option_set_stream_reset_rate_limit(ngopt, 10000, 10000);``` on the server side, it can survive bursts of a few thousand queries.
Note, all of these queries are responded to - nothing is being canceled.

Is it possible to either change ```libnghttp2``` so that responses don't contribute to the reset rate limit or to add an option to enable this behaviour?

Is it possible to either change ```libnghttp2``` so that responses don't contribute to the reset rate limit or to add an option to enable this behaviour?

comment.body:
Yes, I can confirm that our client was sending a ``RST_STREAM`` after receiving a response, causing the bad behaviour.  Removing this addresses the issue.
Thanks again for your help.

comment.body: The mitigation only counts incoming RST_STREAM frame from client.  If it hits, that means client somehow sends RST_STREAM.

comment.body: This is most likely due to the fact that nginx by default limits 1000 requests per h2 connection, and h2load does not create new connection when a previous connection is closed.  See nginx http2_max_requests setting (and keepalive_requests) to override the limit for testing purpose.
